message: Correction of inconsistency. "Since the mid-1980s the Southern Labrador Inuit of NunatuKavut began organizing politically after being geographically cut out of the LIA, however, for political expediency the organization was erroneously called the Labrador Métis Nation". The Labrador Metis Nation (now Nunatukavut) has a website https://www.labradormetis.ca/ showcasing First Nations Indians, hereby demonstrating that they knew as Metis that they were a mix of Indians and not Inuit.

Removal of inconsistency to ensure correctness. "the southern Labrador Inuit in NunatuKavut continued their traditional transhumant semi-nomadic way of life until the mid-1900s". The Nunatukavummuit people usually moved among islands and bays on a seasonal basis. The Nunatukavut people of 2010 were the Labrador Metis Nation in the 90's with a website showcasing North American Native Indians. https://www.labradormetis.ca/ They can't be both Inuit and First Nations Indians of North America.

Nunatukavut is not Inuit and shouldn't be included as such. Natan Obed, president of Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami which represents all Inuit across Canada wrote Prime Minister Justin Trudeau stating that "Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami (ITK) does not accept the federal government’s recognition of NunatuKavut Community Council (NCC) as an “Inuit” organization". https://www.itk.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/20211007-Ltr-PMTrudeau-NunatuKavut.pdf

Information must be written to reflect reality. We must not print misinformation under the guise of anti-censorship, as suggested by CambridgeBayWeather. "Nunatukavut changed from Metis to Inuit". Metis are Mixed-bloods, and Inuit are full-bloods. They can't change, and they can't be both. This is a fact.

Removal for correction of misinformation. Inuit and European heritage as Nunatukavut are, is post-contact, and therefore not Inuit. Inuit are pre-contact with no European history. https://www.relations-inuit.chaire.ulaval.ca/sites/relations-inuit.chaire.ulaval.ca/files/InuitWay_e.pdf. "Prior to contact with Europeans, Inuit were entirely self-sufficient. They lived in small, autonomous, nomadic groups, dependent upon hunting, fishing and gathering for survival and for all their physical needs".

Corrected the population. The Inuit population of those communities as reflected on the Federal Government of Canada's Stats page.https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/abpopprof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=1010011&Data=Count&SearchText=Mary%27s%20Harbour&SearchType=Begins&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=1010011&SEX_ID=1&AGE_ID=1&RESGEO_ID=1.

Removal for correction of misinformation. Nunatukavut are not Inuit. Before 2010 they were the Labrador Metis Nation (mixed-blood), governing 6,000 Metis. In 2010 they became Nunatukavut governing 6,000 Inuit (full-blood). It's not possible. https://www.scribd.com/document/55435993/Labrador-Metis-Association. "The Labrador Metis Nation today represents about 6,000 Métis living in 23 communities in southern Labrador".

Removal for correction of misinformation. Nunatukavut Inuit were Metis. Inuit is pre-contact, and Metis which is a mix is post-contact. There was no British-Inuit Treaty of 1765. There was a basic one-sentence agreement.http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/drachart_christian_larsen_4E.html "On 21 August a form of treaty was made; the Inuit agreed to regard the British flag as a sign of friendship and to stay away from the British fishermen". It states nothing about "southern Labrador Inuit" or rights.

Removal for correction to misinformation. Nunatukavut Inuit were Metis a mix of First Nations Indians and Europeans. Inuit are full-blooded precontact, while Metis are mixed-blooded which is post-contact, and therefore not Inuit or Aboriginal. https://www.heritage.nf.ca/articles/indigenous/southern-inuit-culture.php "Although the Royal Commission on Indigenous Peoples stated in 1996 that Southern Inuit of NunatuKavut (formerly Labrador Inuit-Metis)".

NunatuKavut are not formally in Inuit Nunangat because they are not Inuit. Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami (ITK) president that represents all Inuit groups across Canada wrote Prime Minister Justin Trudeau rejecting NunatuKavut as Inuit of Inuit Nunangathttps://www.itk.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/20211007-Ltr-PMTrudeau-NunatuKavut.pdf

The Treaty of 1765 became the 2010 Labrador Treaty of Southern Labrador Inuit. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1NZu3gcIw16yiYKViMz4CMmvNtwFm3gzO/view. In 2009, the people of Southern Labrador were Metis, with no Inuit ancestry. The only evidence they have to substantiate their "Treaty" claims is their own research.

NunatuKavut claims that their country is "Inuit Nunangat", however, all four organizations that form Inuit Nunangat do not recognize them as Inuit of Inuit Nunangat. https://www.itk.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/20211007-Ltr-PMTrudeau-NunatuKavut.pdf The president of Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami (ITK) that represents all four groups wrote a letter to the Prime Minister to denounce Nunatukvut claims and rights to Aboriginal benefits.

NunatuKavut claims that their country is "Inuit Nunangat", however, all four organizations that form Inuit Nunangat do not recognize them as Inuit of Inuit Nunangat. https://www.itk.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/20211007-Ltr-PMTrudeau-NunatuKavut.pdf the president of Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami (ITK) the represents all four groups wrote a letter to the Prime Minister to denounce Nunatukvut claims and rights to Aboriginal benefits.

Making a correction. It states under "Nomenclature" that they don't know where the name (NunatuKavut) originated, yet it is apparent in their link that they selected the name because it is similar to Nunatsiavut, the name Northern Labrador's Inuit group adopted for the territory it controls. Nunatsiavut means ‘our beautiful land. It's inaccurate and needs correcting. https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/labrador-s-m%C3%A9tis-nation-adopts-new-name-1.927252
Correction to dialect. There is only one Inuit language in Labrador.
Correction to dialect. There was/is only one Inuit dialect in Labrador.
Added link to Labrador Metis text. https://www.labradormetis.ca/
added link to the Labrador Metis text.
added additional text and link along with Nunatukavut formerly the Labrador Metis Nation.
